{{BLP sources|date=July 2016}} {{Infobox football biography | name= Floyd Ayité | image = Floyd Ayite, Fulham FC (42386499962) (cropped).jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Ayité playing for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 2018 | fullname = Floyd Ama Nino Ayité<ref>{{cite web |title=List of players under written contract registered between 01/07/2016 and 31/07/2016 |url=https://www.thefa.com/~/media/files/thefaportal/governance-docs/registrations/player-registration---july-2016.ashx |publisher=The Football Association |format=PDF |page=33 |accessdate=11 November 2016}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1988|12|15|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Bordeaux]], France | height = 1.74 m | position = [[Attacking midfielder]], [[Midfielder#Winger|Winger]] | currentclub = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] | clubnumber = 11 | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = 2008–2011 | clubs1 = [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]] | caps1 = 7 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2008–2009 | clubs2 = → [[Angers SCO|Angers]] (loan) | caps2 = 33 | goals2 = 3 | years3 = 2009–2010 | clubs3 = → [[AS Nancy|Nancy]] (loan) | caps3 = 6 | goals3 = 0 | years4 = 2011–2014 | clubs4 = [[Stade de Reims|Reims]] | caps4 = 73 | goals4 = 10 | years5 = 2014–2016 | clubs5 = [[SC Bastia|Bastia]] | caps5 = 53 | goals5 = 14 | years6 = 2016– | clubs6 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] |caps6 = 70 |goals6 = 13 | nationalyears1 = 2007– | nationalteam1 = [[Togo national football team|Togo]] | nationalcaps1 = 39 | nationalgoals1 = 11 | club-update = 08:51, 10 February 2019 (UTC) | ntupdate = 16 October 2018 }} '''Floyd Ama Nino Ayité''' (born 15 December 1988) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[midfielder]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and the [[Togo national football team|Togo national team]]. He mainly plays a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]]. He is [[Jonathan Ayité]]'s younger brother.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/sport/football/1681850/fulham-star-floyd-ayite-opens-up-on-togo-bus-attack-at-2010-african-nations-cup-which-tragically-left-four-dead/|title=Fulham star Floyd Ayite opens up on Togo bus attack at 2010 African Nations Cup which tragically left four dead|first=Sarah|last=Boyall|newspaper=[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]|date=27 August 2016}}</ref>
==Career== Ayité was born in [[Bordeaux]], and started his career as a footballer for home town [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]]. Making his debut for the club in 2008. Loan spells at [[Angers SCO|Angers]] and [[AS Nancy|Nancy]] followed.
In 2011, Ayité signed for [[Stade de Reims|Reims]], where he made 73 league appearances scoring 10 goals. His form for [[Stade de Reims|Reims]] saw him join [[SC Bastia|Bastia]] in 2014 where he scored 5 goals in 28 league games in his first season at the club.
On 1 July 2016, Ayité signed for English [[Football League Championship|Championship]] club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] for an undisclosed fee, signing a three- year contract, with a club option of a further twelve months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36686822|title=Floyd Ayite: Fulham bring in Togo forward from Bastia|first=|last=|work=BBC Sport|date=1 July 2016|accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> He scored his first goals for Fulham when he scored twice in a 4–4 draw with [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on 10 December 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38192220 |title=Wolves 4–4 Fulham |publisher=BBC |date=10 December 2016 |accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>
==International career== Despite being born in France, Ayité decide to follow in the footsteps of his older brother [[Jonathan Ayité]] and represent [[Togo national football team|Togo]], making his debut in 2008. On 14 November 2009, he scored his first goal for Togo, against [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]].
==Career statistics== ===Club=== {{updated|match played 6 January 2019}}
