{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Maxime Le Marchand | image = Chelsea 2 Fulham 0 (Maxime Le Marchand).jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Le Marchand playing for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 2018 | fullname = Maxime Le Marchand<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/844127 |title=2018/19 Premier League squads confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=3 September 2018 |accessdate=4 September 2018}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|10|11|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Saint-Malo]], France | height = 1.84 m | position = [[Left back]] | currentclub = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] | clubnumber = 20 | youthyears1 = 1995–2000 | youthclubs1 = [[US Saint-Malo|Saint-Malo]] | youthyears2 = 2000–2009 | youthclubs2 = [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]] | years1 = 2009–2010 | clubs1 = [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]] | caps1 = 0 | goals1 = 0 | years2 = 2009–2010 | clubs2 = → [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]] (loan) | caps2 = 27 | goals2 = 1 | years3 = 2010–2012 | clubs3 = [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre B]] | caps3 = 9 | goals3 = 1 | years4 = 2010–2015 | clubs4 = [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]] | caps4 = 134 | goals4 = 4 | years5 = 2015–2018 | clubs5 = [[OGC Nice|Nice]] | caps5 = 65 | goals5 = 1 | years6 = 2016 | clubs6 = [[OGC Nice|Nice B]] | caps6 = 1 | goals6 = 0 | years7 = 2018– | clubs7 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] | caps7 = 19 | goals7 = 0 | club-update = 08:59, 10 February 2019 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = }} '''Maxime Le Marchand''' (born 11 October 1989) is a French professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[left back]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].
==Club career== ===Youth career=== Le Marchand was born in the port city of [[Saint-Malo]] in Brittany and began his youth football career with his hometown club, [[US Saint-Malo|Saint-Malo]]. In 2000, he joined the prestigious youth academy of [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]]. Upon arriving at the club, Le Marchand initially joined as a [[Midfielder|left-sided midfielder]], but eventually moved to the [[left-back]] role. After ascending the youth ranks, he added the [[Midfielder#Winger|left winger]] position into his arsenal often playing both positions in dual roles. Between 2006 and 2008, he was frustrated by injuries to his ankle, but was still able to celebrate Rennes's capturing of the under-18 championship for the 2006–07 season, and the [[Coupe Gambardella]] in 2008 alongside his Rennes teammates [[Yann M'Vila]], [[Damien Le Tallec]], and [[Yacine Brahimi]].<ref>[http://www.stade-rennais-online.com/Maxime-Le-Marchand.html Maxime Le Marchand]</ref>
===Le Havre=== Following the [[Ligue 1 2008–09|2008–09 season]], Le Marchand signed his first professional contract, agreeing to a three-year deal with [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]].<ref>[http://www.staderennais.com/index.php?rb=22&id=AT5107 Un contrat de 3 ans pour Maxime Le Marchand]</ref> Though he was contracted to Rennes, he was not inserted onto their senior team and, instead, sent on loan to [[Ligue 2]] club [[Le Havre AC|Le Havre]] to receive regular playing time.<ref>[http://www.stade-rennais-online.com/+3235-Pret-officiel-Le-Marchand-au+.html Prêt, officiel : Le Marchand au Havre]</ref> At Le Havre, he was assigned the number 21 shirt. On 7 August 2009, he made his professional first team debut in the club's 1–1 Ligue 2 away draw with [[CS Sedan Ardennes|Sedan]], playing the entire match.<ref name="MaximeLeMarchardSoccerway">{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/maxime-le-marchand/87243/ |title=Maxime Le Marchand |website=Soccerway}}</ref><ref>[http://www.lfp.fr/coupeLigue/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2009/2010&code_evt=D2&code_jr_tr=T01&num_ordre=2 Tours v. Le Havre Match Report]{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He scored his first competitive goal for the club's first team, on 30 August 2009, in their 1–1 Ligue 2 away draw with [[Vannes OC|Vannes]].<ref>[http://www.lfp.fr/ligue2/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2009/2010&code_evt=D2&code_jr_tr=J05&num_ordre=10 Vannes v. Le Havre Match Report]{{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090912023809/http://www.lfp.fr/ligue2/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2009%2F2010&code_evt=D2&code_jr_tr=J05&num_ordre=10 |date=12 September 2009 }}</ref> After a successful season on loan with Le Havre, on 23 June 2010, Le Marchand signed permanently for the club.<ref>[http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100623_104523_lemarchand-signe-au-havre.html Lemarchand signe au Havre (off.)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100626041737/http://www.francefootball.fr/FF/breves2010/20100623_104523_lemarchand-signe-au-havre.html |date=26 June 2010 }}</ref>
===Nice=== on 25 June 2015, Le Marchand joined [[Ligue 1]] club [[OGC Nice|Nice]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Maxime Le Marchand officiellement niçois |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Maxime-le-marchand-officiellement-a-nice/569343 |newspaper=L'Équipe |date=25 June 2015}}</ref> On 8 August 2015, he made his competitive debut for Nice in their opening match of the [[2015–16 Ligue 1]] season, playing the entire match in the 2–1 home loss to [[AS Monaco|Monaco]]. Seven days later, he scored in the 42nd minute to register his first competitive goal for Nice in the 3–3 Ligue 1 away draw with [[Troyes AC|Troyes]].<ref name="MaximeLeMarchardSoccerway"/>
On 2 November 2017, Le Marchand scored an [[own goal]] three minutes into second-half added time in the [[2017–18 UEFA Europa League group stage]] 1–0 loss to [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], causing Nice to slump to their sixth straight defeat in all competitions.<ref>{{cite web |title=OL close in on knockout phase |url=http://www.ligue1.com/autresCompetitions/article/ol-close-in-on-knockout-phase.htm |publisher=Ligue 1 |date=2 November 2017}}</ref>
===Fulham=== On 12 July 2018, Le Marchand signed for newly promoted [[Premier League]] side [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fulhamfc.com/news/2018/july/12/le-marchand-arrives |title=Le Marchand Joins Fulham |publisher=Fulham F.C. |accessdate=12 July 2018 |date=12 July 2018}}</ref>
