{{Use British English|date=November 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}} {{Infobox football biography | name = Cyrus Christie | image = Cyrus Christie, Fulham Fc (42386429892).jpg | image_size = 200 | caption = Christie warming up for [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in 2018 | fullname = Cyrus Sylvester Frederick Christie<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.efl.com/news/2016/june/efl-club-retained-and-released-lists-published/ |title=EFL: Club retained and released lists published |publisher=English Football League |date=23 June 2016 |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|9|30|df=y}}<ref>{{Hugman|22574|accessdate=7 November 2017}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Coventry]], England | height = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=Glenda |editor1-last=Rollin |editor2-first=Jack |editor2-last=Rollin |title=Sky Sports Football Yearbook 2012–2013 |year=2012 |publisher=Headline Publishing Group |location=London |isbn=978-0-7553-6356-8 |page=457 |edition=43rd}}</ref> | position = [[Right back]] | currentclub = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] | clubnumber = 22 | youthyears1 = {{0|0000}}–2010 | youthclubs1 = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] | years1 = 2010–2014 | clubs1 = [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] | caps1 = 102 | goals1 = 3 | years2 = 2011 | clubs2 = → [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Town]] (loan) | caps2 = 5 | goals2 = 0 | years3 = 2011 | clubs3 = → [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]] (loan) | caps3 = 8 | goals3 = 0 | years4 = 2014–2017 | clubs4 = [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] | caps4 = 107 | goals4 = 2 | years5 = 2017–2018 | clubs5 = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] | caps5 = 25 | goals5 = 1 | years6 = 2018– | clubs6 = [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] | caps6 = 25 | goals6 = 0 | nationalyears1 = 2014– | nationalteam1 = [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] | nationalcaps1 = 22 | nationalgoals1 = 2 | club-update = 09:02, 10 February 2019 (UTC) | nationalteam-update = 03:22, 19 November 2018 (UTC) }} '''Cyrus Sylvester Frederick Christie''' (born 30 September 1992) is a professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)|defender]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] and the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland national team]].
==Early and personal life== Christie was born in [[Coventry]], West Midlands.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.11v11.com/players/cyrus-christie-236390/ |title=Cyrus Christie |work=11v11.com |publisher=AFS Enterprises |accessdate=9 November 2017}}</ref> He is a nephew of the late boxer [[Errol Christie]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dutton|first1=Tom|title=Nephew Cyrus Christie 'heatbroken' after former British boxer Errol Christie dies aged 53|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/other-sports/nephew-cyrus-christie-heatbroken-after-former-british-boxer-errol-christie-dies-aged-53-a3562591.html|accessdate=15 June 2017|newspaper=London Evening Standard|date=12 June 2017}}</ref>
==Career== ===Coventry City=== Christie made his first-team debut for [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] against [[Morecambe F.C.|Morecambe]] on 10 August 2010, in a 2–0 away defeat in the [[EFL Cup|League Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0,,10269~53930,00.html |title=Morecambe 2–0 Coventry City |publisher=Coventry City F.C. |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=10 August 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120913062742/http://www.ccfc.co.uk/page/MatchReport/0%2C%2C10269~53930%2C00.html |archivedate=13 September 2012}}</ref>
He joined [[National League North|Conference North]] club [[Nuneaton Town F.C.|Nuneaton Town]] on [[Loan (sports)|loan]] in January 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pitchero.com/clubs/nuneatontownfootballclub/news/christie-joins-boro-239819.html|title=Christie Joins Boro|publisher=Nuneaton Town F.C.|date=14 January 2011|accessdate=27 February 2011 |via=Pitchero}}</ref> but was recalled by Coventry after two starts and three substitute appearances.<ref name=Nuneaton1011/> He then went on a 'work experience' loan to another Conference North club [[Hinckley United F.C.|Hinckley United]], in February 2011,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hinckleyunited.com/news/Cyrus-Christie.html|title=Hinckley loan Christie|publisher=Hinckley United F.C.|date=14 February 2011|accessdate=15 February 2011}}</ref> where he made eight appearances.<ref name=Hinckley1011/>
After Coventry's first league win of the 2011–12 season, a 2–0 home win against [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], Christie made it into the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] Team of the Week.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The following season, he was in the League One side of the week after putting a man of the match performance against [[Leyton Orient F.C.|Leyton Orient]].{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The following game on 3 November, in the first round of the [[FA Cup]], he scored his first goal in a 3–0 win against [[Arlesey Town F.C.|Arlesey Town]] and was praised by manager [[Mark Robins]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Crowley|first1=Kieran|title=Robins lauds Christie effect|url=https://www.ccfc.co.uk/news/2012/november/robins-lauds-christie-effect/|accessdate=21 November 2017|publisher=Coventry City F.C.|date=3 November 2012}}</ref> On 8 December he scored his first league goal in a 5–1 home win over [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Poole|first1=Alan|title=Cyrus Christie set for advanced role in trip to Doncaster|url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/sport/football/football-news/cyrus-christie-set-advanced-role-3015896|accessdate=21 November 2017|work=Coventry Telegraph|date=15 December 2012}}</ref>
In 2012, Coventry were relegated to League One.{{cn|date=January 2019}}
===Derby County=== On 10 July 2014, Christie returned to the Championship on a three-year contract at Derby County. He was out of contract at Coventry, but the two clubs agreed an undisclosed fee for the player since he came through Coventry's academy and was under 23 years old.<ref name="Derby County Sign Coventry City's Cyrus Christie">{{cite web|title=Derby County Sign Coventry City's Cyrus Christie|url=http://www.dcfc.co.uk/news/article/derby-county-sign-coventry-citys-cyrus-christie-1737811.aspx|publisher=Derby County F.C.|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref>
Christie made his debut against [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] on 9 August, where he provided an assist for goalscorer [[Jeff Hendrick]] in a 1–0 home victory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Derby 1&nbsp;– 0 Rotherham|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28646610|publisher=BBC|accessdate=9 August 2014}}</ref> On 20 February 2016, he scored his first Rams goal in his 74th appearance, a 3–1 win at [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. His short-range strike with seven minutes remaining was his first club goal since March 2013 and ended an eight-game winless run at the start of the year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Watson|first1=Chris|title=Derby County: Cyrus Christie targets more goals after opening Rams account at Brentford|url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/derby-county-cyrus-christie-targets-goals-opening/story-28779229-detail/story.html|accessdate=15 June 2017|work=Derby Telegraph|date=22 February 2016}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
===Middlesbrough=== On 7 July 2017, Christie and [[Jonny Howson]] moved for undisclosed fees to newly relegated Championship club [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Jonny Howson and Cyrus Christie join Middlesbrough for undisclosed fees|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40495386|accessdate=21 November 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=7 July 2017}}</ref> He made his debut on 5 August as the season began with a 1–0 loss at [[Wolverhampton Wanderers]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=MacInnes|first1=Paul|title=Leo Bonatini pounces as Wolves beat Middlesbrough in battle of big spenders|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/aug/05/wolves-middlesbrough-championship-match-report|accessdate=21 November 2017|work=The Observer|date=5 August 2017}}</ref> and scored his first goal for the club in a 1–1 draw away to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 23 September.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41289622 |title=Fulham 1–1 Middlesbrough |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 September 2017 |accessdate=24 September 2017}}</ref>
===Fulham=== On 31 January 2018, Christie joined Championship side [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/42514389 |title=Transfer Deals – January 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 January 2018 |accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> He made his debut for Fulham in a 1–1 draw at [[Bristol City]] on 21 February 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/43053718|title=Bristol City 1–1 Fulham |publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 February 2018|accessdate=22 February 2018}}</ref> At the end of the season, Fulham were promoted to the Premier League.
Christie scored his first goal for Fulham in an [[EFL Cup]] tie against [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] on 25 September 2018.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fulham ease past Millwall and introduce teenage prospect |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/fulham-ease-past-millwall-and-introduce-teenage-prospect-37355070.html|accessdate=26 September 2018|publisher=belfasttelegraph.co.uk|date=25 September 2018}}</ref>
==International career== Born in England, Christie was eligible to represent the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]] through his grandmother from Dublin.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/DERBY-COUNTY-Rams-defender-Cyrus-Christie/story-24508473-detail/story.html |title=Derby County: Rams defender Cyrus Christie receives first Republic of Ireland call-up |newspaper=Derby Telegraph |date=10 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111171527/http://www.derbytelegraph.co.uk/DERBY-COUNTY-Rams-defender-Cyrus-Christie/story-24508473-detail/story.html |archivedate=11 November 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, Ireland manager [[Martin O'Neill]] reached out to Christie over representing the Republic of Ireland having been impressed with his performances for Derby at the beginning of the 2013–14 season following his move from Coventry.<ref>{{cite news |title=Derby defender Cyrus Christie on verge of Ireland call-up following talks with Martin O'Neill|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/international-soccer/derby-defender-cyrus-christie-on-verge-of-ireland-callup-following-talks-with-martin-oneill-30651639.html|newspaper=Irish Independent|accessdate= 9 October 2014}}</ref> On 10 November, Christie was called into the Ireland squad for a [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] match against [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]], and a friendly against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]].<ref>{{cite web|title=David McGoldrick and Cyrus Christie named in Ireland squad to face Scotland|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/3942/ireland/2014/11/10/6010891/david-mcgoldrick-and-cyrus-christie-named-in-ireland-squad|publisher=Goal.com|accessdate= 10 November 2014}}</ref>
On 18 November 2014, Christie made his international debut for Ireland against the United States, in a 4–1 win at the [[Aviva Stadium]], with O'Neill praising his performance.<ref>{{cite news| first = Daniel| last = McDonnell| title = Ireland's new blood lifts the mood for happy O'Neill| url = http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/european-championships/irelands-new-blood-lifts-the-mood-for-happy-oneill-30756421.html| newspaper = Irish Independent| location = Ireland| date = 18 November 2014| accessdate = 20 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thescore.ie/martin-oneill-praises-debutant-cyrus-christie-1787300-Nov2014/|title=Martin O'Neill praises 'brilliant' debutant Cyrus Christie|publisher=The Score.ie|date=18 November 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129050256/http://www.thescore.ie/martin-oneill-praises-debutant-cyrus-christie-1787300-Nov2014/|archivedate=29 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He scored his first international goal on his next cap, a 4–0 away win over [[Gibraltar national football team|Gibraltar]] on 4 September 2015 which was his competitive debut in [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Cyrus Christie marks competitive debut with first Republic of Ireland goal against Gibraltar|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9979270/cyrus-christie-marks-competitive-debut-with-first-republic-of-ireland-goal-against-gibraltar|accessdate=15 June 2017|publisher=Sky Sports|date=4 September 2015}}</ref> That 8 October, he played in a victory over world champions [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in another qualifier, and was praised for his contributions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cyrus Christie savours scalp of world champions|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/soccer/2015/1009/733525-christie-savours/|accessdate=15 June 2017|publisher=RTÉ Sport |date=9 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Cyrus Christie & Republic of Ireland beat Germany|url=http://www.arete.co.uk/latest/cyrus-christie-republic-of-ireland-beat-germany/|accessdate=15 June 2017|publisher=Areté|date=9 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170905100128/http://www.arete.co.uk/latest/cyrus-christie-republic-of-ireland-beat-germany/|archive-date=5 September 2017|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
Christie scored an [[own goal]] on 14 November 2017 as the Irish lost 5–1 at home to [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] in a [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] qualifying play-off. He was subsequently the target of online racist abuse, which the [[Football Association of Ireland]] reported to the police.<ref>{{cite news|title=FAI report alleged racist abuse of Cyrus Christie to police|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42060300|accessdate=21 November 2017|publisher=BBC Sport|date=20 November 2017}}</ref>
